# What criteria are used to decide which countries send assistance and how is the assistance coordinated?

## Summary
When a disaster like an earthquake occurs, various countries vow to send assistance based on their capabilities and the needs of the affected area. For instance, in response to the earthquake in Turkey and Syria, countries such as the United States and Germany offered to provide assistance (Contexts 1 & 2). The U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID) activates teams trained in Urban Search and Rescue (US&R) to work with other organizations on the ground (Context 1). These teams, like those from Los Angeles and Fairfax County, Virginia, comprise of professionals with highly technical skills needed in rescue operations (Context 1 & 5).

Countries like the Netherlands are also willing to send help in the form of search and rescue teams when an international call for assistance is made by the affected state, as was the case with the Turkish Disaster and Emergency Management Agency (AFAD) (Context 4). 

The coordination of relief efforts can involve various government agencies. For example, in the U.S., the United States Transportation Command (USTRANSCOM) provides rescue equipment, while the U.S. Department of State coordinates all U.S. government support to the affected nation via relevant missions (Context 5).

